{{reli-philo-stub}}

In [[category theory]], a branch of mathematics, a '''stable model category''' is a [[pointed model category]] in which the suspension functor is an equivalence of the homotopy category with itself.
The prototypical examples are the category of [[spectrum (topology)|spectra]] in the [[stable homotopy theory]] and the category of chain complex of ''R''-modules. On the other hand, the category of pointed topological spaces and the category of pointed simplicial sets are not stable model categories.
Any stable model category is equivalent to a category of [[presheaf of spectra|presheaves of spectra]].{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
